40 years new pigments have been discovered, new genetic mechanisms have been described, new theories have been developed, and hundreds of new experiments have been conducted. Geoffrey Hill and Kevin McGraw have assembled the world's leading experts in perception, measurement, and control of bird coloration to contribute to this book. This sumptuously illustrated volume synthesizes more than 1,500 technical papers in this field. The focus is on the three primary mechanisms of color production--melanin pigmentation, carotenoid pigmentation, and structural coloration--but less common as well as newly described mechanisms of color production are also reviewed in detail. The visual perception of birds and the best ways to collect and analyze color data are, for the first time, presented as part of the review of mechanisms of coloration. This book will be essential reading for biologists studying animal coloration, but it will also be treasured by anyone curious about how birds produce and perceive their bold and brilliant color displays.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aBirdsxColor. 7aNATURE / Animals / Birds.2bisacsh1 aAndersson, Staffan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuthill, Innes C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Geoffrey E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Geoffrey E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKimball, Rebecca T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGraw, Kevin J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontgomerie, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMundy, Nicholas I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrager, Maria, ec